Overall Idea of This Pipeline

This pipeline does:

Pull code from GitHub
Install Node.js dependencies
Build Docker image
Push image to Docker Hub
Deploy app to Azure Kubernetes Service (AKS) using Helm
Verify deployment
Enable autoscaling (HPA)
⚙️ 1. Pipeline Block
pipeline {
    agent any
👉 Meaning:
pipeline {} → Jenkins Declarative Pipeline starts
agent any → run this pipeline on any available Jenkins agent (node/VM)
🌍 2. Environment Block
environment {
    NAMESPACE = "default"
    KUBECONFIG = "/var/jenkins_home/.kube/config"
}
👉 Meaning:
🔹 NAMESPACE
Kubernetes namespace = default
All deployments will go inside this namespace
🔹 KUBECONFIG
Path where Jenkins finds Kubernetes credentials
Allows Jenkins to run:
kubectl get pods
kubectl apply
etc.

👉 Without this, Jenkins cannot talk to AKS cluster.

📥 3. Stage: Checkout
stage('Checkout') {
👉 What it does:

Pulls source code from GitHub repo.

checkout scmGit(
    branches: [[name: '*/master']],
Pulls master branch
credentialsId: 'github',
Uses stored GitHub credentials in Jenkins
url: 'https://github.com/nishas01/bootcampnodejsAPP.git'
GitHub repo URL
✅ Output:

Your app code is now inside Jenkins workspace.

📦 4. Stage: Install Dependencies
stage('Install Dependencies')
👉 What it does:

Installs Node.js packages (npm install)

docker.image('node:20').inside {
    sh 'npm install'
}
🔥 Important concept:
Jenkins temporarily runs a Docker container with Node 20
Inside that container:
your code is mounted
npm install runs
📌 Why Docker here?
No need to install Node on Jenkins machine
Clean, isolated environment
🐳 5. Stage: Docker Build
stage('Docker Build')
👉 What it does:

Builds Docker image from your Dockerfile

sh 'docker build -t nisha0111/demoproject:v4 .'
Breakdown:
docker build → create image
-t → tag name
nisha0111/demoproject → DockerHub repo
v4 → version tag
. → current directory (Dockerfile location)
📌 Output:

You now have a local Docker image:

nisha0111/demoproject:v4
🔐 6. Stage: Docker Login
stage('Docker Login')
👉 What it does:

Logs Jenkins into Docker Hub.

withCredentials([usernamePassword(
    credentialsId: 'docker-token',
Uses Jenkins stored credentials (docker-token)
usernameVariable: 'USER',
passwordVariable: 'PASS'
Injects credentials as environment variables
sh 'echo $PASS | docker login -u $USER --password-stdin'
🔥 Meaning:
Secure login to Docker Hub
Password is NOT exposed in logs
📤 7. Stage: Docker Push
stage('Docker Push')
👉 What it does:

Pushes Docker image to Docker Hub.

sh 'docker push nisha0111/demoproject:v4'
📌 Result:

Image is now stored in:
👉 Docker Hub repository
so Kubernetes can pull it later.

☸️ 8. Stage: Deploy to AKS (Helm)
stage('Deploy to AKS (Helm)')
👉 What it does:

Deploys application to Kubernetes using Helm chart.

kubectl get nodes
Checks cluster connectivity
🚀 Helm deployment:
helm upgrade --install myapp ./helm-chart
Breakdown:
helm → Kubernetes package manager
upgrade --install →
install if not present
upgrade if already exists
myapp → release name
./helm-chart → chart folder
🔧 Custom values:
--set image.repository=nisha0111/demoproject
--set image.tag=v4

👉 This tells Kubernetes:

use this Docker image
version = v4
📌 Result:
Pods get created in AKS
Your Node.js app runs in Kubernetes
🔍 9. Stage: Verify Deployment
stage('Verify Deployment')
👉 What it does:

Checks if app is running properly.

kubectl get pods -n default
shows running containers
kubectl get svc -n default
shows services (exposes app)
kubectl get ingress -n default
shows external access URL (if ingress used)
📌 Purpose:

This is post-deployment validation

📈 10. Stage: Apply HPA (Autoscaling)
stage('Apply HPA')
👉 What it does:

Applies Kubernetes Horizontal Pod Autoscaler.

kubectl apply -f helm-chart/templates/hpa.yaml
Creates autoscaling rule
kubectl get hpa -n default
Shows autoscaler status
📌 What HPA does:

Automatically increases/decreases pods based on CPU/memory usage.

Example:

Traffic increases → more pods
Traffic decreases → fewer pods
